variables.desc: Interface information table.
variables.name: intfs_table

variables.desc: Interface name.
variables.name: $intf

variables.desc: Average number of bits and packets received per second in the last 5 minutes. If the interface is not in promiscuous mode, it senses network traffic that it sends and receives (rather than all network traffic).
variables.name: $input_rate_time

variables.desc: Average number of bits and packets transmitted per second in the last 5 minutes. If the interface is not in promiscuous mode, it senses network traffic that it sends and receives (rather than all network traffic).
variables.name: $output_rate_time

variables.desc: Number of packets received on the interface that were successfully delivered to higher layers.
variables.name: $pkts_input

variables.desc: Number of received packets that were too small to be handled.
variables.name: $runts

variables.desc: Number of received packets that were too large to be handled.
variables.name: $giants

variables.desc: Total number of received packets that contain errors and hence cannot be delivered. Compare this to total input drops, which counts packets that were not delivered despite containing no errors.
variables.name: $input_error

variables.desc: Number of packets that failed the CRC check.
variables.name: $crc

variables.desc: Number of packets received on the interface that were successfully delivered to higher layers.
variables.name: $pkts_output

variables.desc: Number of times that the receiver hardware was unable to handle received data to a hardware buffer because the input rate exceeded the receiver's ability to handle the data.
variables.name: $output_error

variables.desc: Since a Token Ring cannot have collisions, this statistic is nonzero only if an unusual event occurred when frames were being queued or dequeued by the system software.
variables.name: $collisions

variables.desc: Number of late collisions. Late collision happens when a collision occurs after transmitting the preamble. The most common cause of late collisions is that your Ethernet cable segments are too long for the speed at which you are transmitting.
variables.name: $late_collision

variables.desc: Deferred indicates that the chip had to defer while ready to transmit a frame because the carrier was asserted.
variables.name: $deferred

variables.desc: IP address of the interface.
variables.name: $ip_addr

variables.desc: The MTU is the maximum packet size that can be transmitted over the interface.
variables.name: $mtu

variables.desc:
"Value of the bandwidth parameter that has been configured for the interface (in kilobits per second). 
The bandwidth parameter is used to compute IGRP metrics only. If the interface is attached to a serial line with a line speed that does not match the default (1536 or 1544 for T1 and 56 for a standard synchr-onous serial line), use the bandwidth command to specify the correct line speed for this serial line."
variables.name: $bw

variables.desc: Type of link connection configured for the physical interface.
variables.name: $duplex

variables.desc: Speed at which the interface is running.
variables.name: $speed

variables.desc: MAC address of interface.
variables.name: $mac_addr

variables.desc: Average number of bits and packets received per second in the last 5 minutes. If the interface is not in promiscuous mode, it senses network traffic that it sends and receives (rather than all network traffic).
variables.name: $input_rate_bit

variables.desc: Average number of bits and packets transmitted per second in the last 5 minutes. If the interface is not in promiscuous mode, it senses network traffic that it sends and receives (rather than all network traffic).
variables.name: $output_rate_bit

variables.desc: Broadcast address of the interface.
variables.name: $broadcast_addr

variables.desc: Number of recived broadcast packets.
variables.name: $re_broadcast_pkts

variables.desc: Number of recived multicast packets.
variables.name: $re_multicast_pkts

variables.desc: Number of sent broadcast packets.
variables.name: $se_broadcast_pkts

variables.desc: Number of sent multicast packets.
variables.name: $se_multicast_pkts

variables.desc: Number of input pause packets.
variables.name: $input_pause

variables.desc: Number of output pause packets.
variables.name: $output_pause
